www.rottentomatoes.com/m/creepshow-iii/ |title=Creepshow 3 |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date= |accessdate=2012-08-25}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | 2010s\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Children of the Corn: Genesis]]''\n| [[Joel Soisson]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Sequel to 1984's ''Children of the Corn''. \n| [[Dimension Extreme]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" {{N/A}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Children of the Corn: Runaway''\n| [[John Gulager]]\n| [[Lionsgate Films]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Comic books==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Comic\n! Based on\n! Publisher\n|-\n| 1981\n|''The Lawnmower Man'' in ''[[Bizarre Adventures]]'' #29\n| Based on the short story ''[[The Lawnmower Man]]''\n|[[Marvel Comics]]\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Creepshow (comics)|Creepshow]]''\n| Based on the ''[[Creepshow]]'' film\n| [[Plume (publisher)|Plume]]\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[The Talisman (comics)|The Talisman]]''<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.stephenking.com/promo/talisman_gn/|title=The Talisman Graphic Novel Series \u2013 Coming Fall 2009|publisher=Stephenking.com|date=October 13, 2008|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|Based on the novel ''[[The Talisman (King & Straub novel)|The Talisman]]''\n|[[Del Rey Books|Del Rey]]\n|-\n|2010\n|''N.''\n|Based on the novella ''[[N. (novella)|N.]]''\n|[[Marvel Comics]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2012\n|''Road Rage''\n|Based on the novella ''[[Throttle (novella)|Throttle]]'', co-authored with his son, [[Joe Hill (writer)|Joe Hill]]\n|[[IDW Publishing]]\n|-\n|''The Little Green God of Agony''\n|Based on the short story of the same name\n|Free web-comic on Stephen King's official website<ref>{{cite web |last1=Armitage |first1=Hugh |title=NYCC: Stephen King debuts webcomic adaptation |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/comics/a431593/nycc-stephen-king-debuts-webcomic-adaptation/ |website=[[Digital Spy]] |date=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sleeping Beauties''\n|Based on the novel ''[[Sleeping Beauties (novel)|Sleeping Beauties]]'', co-authored with his son, [[Owen King]]\n|IDW Publishing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/07/sleeping-beauties-tale-by-stephen-king-owen-king-set-for-2020-comic-book-series-1202646792/|title=\u2018Sleeping Beauties\u2019: Tale By Stephen King & Owen King Set For 2020 Comic Book Series|first=Geoff|last=Boucher|date=16 July 2019|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=18 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" |''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower]]''\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger Born]]''\n| rowspan=\"6\" | Spin-offs from the ''[[The Dark Tower (series)|Dark Tower]]'' novels\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Marvel Comics]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: The Long Road Home]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: Treachery]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2009\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: The Sorcerer]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: The Fall of Gilead]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: Battle of Jericho Hill]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2010\n| ''[[The Dark Tower: The Journey Begins|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 The Journey Begins]]'' \n| Based on the novel ''[[The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger]]''\n| rowspan=\"13\" | [[Marvel Comics]]\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 The Little Sisters of Eluria]]''\n| Based on the short story ''[[The Little Sisters of Eluria]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 The Battle of Tull]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Based on the novel ''[[The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 The Way Station]]''\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 The Man in Black]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2013\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 Sheemie's Tale]]''\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Spin-off from the ''[[The Dark Tower (series)|Dark Tower]]'' novels\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 Evil Ground]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Gunslinger \u2013 So Fell Lord Perth]]''\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Drawing of the Three \u2013 The Prisoner]]''\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Based on the novel ''[[The Dark Tower II: The Drawing of the Three]]''\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Drawing of the Three \u2013 House of Cards]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Drawing of the Three \u2013 Lady of Shadows]]''\n|-\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Drawing of the Three \u2013 Bitter Medicine]]''\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Dark Tower (comics)|The Dark Tower: The Drawing of the Three \u2013 The Prisoner]]''\n| Based on the novel ''[[The Dark Tower III: The Waste Lands]]''\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | ''[[The Stand (comics)|The Stand]]''\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Stand: Captain Trips]]''\n| rowspan=\"6\" | Based on the novel ''[[The Stand]]''\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Marvel Comics]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2009\n| ''[[The Stand: American Nightmares]]''\n|-\n| ''The Stand: Soul Survivors''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/catalog/the_stand~colon~_soul_survivors.0000.1 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20091022133509/http://marvel.com/catalog/the_stand~colon~_soul_survivors.0000.1 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-10-22 |title=THE STAND: SOUL SURVIVORS # 1 |publisher=Marvel }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''The Stand: Hardcases''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''The Stand: No Mans Land''\n|-\n| ''The Stand: Night Has Come''\n|}\n\n==Stage==\n{{more citations needed section|date=April 2016}}\n*1988: ''[[Carrie (musical)|Carrie]]'' is notorious for its history as a flop on Broadway, and has gained a [[cult following]] in recent years. The musical was revived at the [[Lucille Lortel Theatre]] in New York, directed by [[Stafford Arima]] from January until April 2012. On September 25, 2012, the first official cast recording was released. The new production is currently available to license for professional and amateur productions from Rodgers & Hammerstein Theatricals.\n*1990: ''Ghost Stories'' was an adaptation of Stephen King's short stories \"The Return of Timmy Baterman,\" about zombies; \"[[Strawberry Spring]],\" about a campus serial killer; \"[[Gray Matter (short story)|Gray Matter]],\" a black comedy about a hideous mutation caused by a bottle of beer; \"[[Uncle Otto's Truck]],\" and \"[[The Boogeyman (short story)|The Boogeyman]],\" about a distraught father's encounter with a child-killing closet monster, as well as selections from ''[[Pet Sematary]]''. Adapted and directed by Robert Pridham, the play premiered at the Arts Center Theatre at [[Kent Place School]] in Summit, New Jersey, and toured the United States in the mid-1990s.\n*1993: ''[[Rage (Stephen King novel)|Rage]]'' stage play produced by [[Shane Black]] and directed by Jim Birge. Originally titled ''Getting It On'', it was intended to premiere in [[Jasper, Indiana]], but scheduling and venue issues forced it to move to the [[VFW]] in [[Santa Claus, Indiana]], where it ran from April 23 to May 1. Venue problems caused the final show, on May 2, to be canceled.\n*2005: ''[[Misery (novel)|Misery]]'' stage play by [[Simon Moore (writer)|Simon Moore]] based on 1987 novel. Another adaptation, written by [[William Goldman]] (who wrote the 1990 film), premiered on Broadway in 2015 with [[Bruce Willis]] and [[Laurie Metcalf]]. A musical version also exists, written by Jeff Hockhauser and Bob Johnson. While it has not been staged, a demo recording has circulated on the internet in recent years.\n*2009: ''[[Rita Hayworth and Shawshank Redemption]]'' was dramatized by [[Dave Johns]] and [[Owen O'Neill]] for the [[Gaiety Theatre, Dublin]].<ref name=\"ShawshankDublin\">{{cite web |title=Actors Who Have Served Their Time Bring Jail Hell Alive; THEATRE |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-199945271/actors-who-have-served-their-time-bring-jail-hell |last=Moffatt |first=Michael |work=[[Irish Mail on Sunday]] |accessdate=October 30, 2014| date=May 17, 2009}} {{Subscription required |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ShawshankLondon\">{{cite web |title=A Little Escapism in King's Grim Classic; THEATRE |url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-200456865/a-little-escapism-in-king-s-grim-classic-theatre |last=Moffatt |first=Michael |work=[[Mail on Sunday]] |accessdate=October 30, 2014| date=May 24, 2009}} {{Subscription required |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> A later version, directed by [[Peter Sheridan]], had its world premiere at the Peter Sheridan Theatre in London in September 2010. A production was mounted at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] directed by Lucy Pitman-Wallace in August 2013.<ref name=\"ShawshankEdinburgh\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2013/aug/11/the-shawshank-redemption-edinburgh-review |title=The Shawshank Redemption \u2013 Edinburgh festival 2013 review |work=The Guardian |date = August 11, 2013|accessdate=October 30, 2014}}</ref> In April 2019, The Shawshank Redemption made its North American debut at the Metropolitan Ensemble Theatre in Kansas City, Missouri, directed by Bob Paisley. It garnered great reviews from critics during its run. It featured Keenan Ramos as Red, Chris Roady as Andy Defresne, S.E. Perry as Warden Stammas, Tim Ahlenius as Hadley, Chad Burris as Boggs Diamond, Dan Daly as Pinky, Kevin Fewell as Brooksie, Christopher Preyer as Rooster, Larry Goodman as Dawkins, Nick Hazel as Entwhistle, Evan Lovelace as Tommy, Andrew Paredes as Rico, and Alex Paxton as inmate/guard.\n*2012: ''[[Ghost Brothers of Darkland County]]'', an original musical with book by Stephen King and music and lyrics by [[John Mellencamp]]. After a week of previews, it ran at Atlanta's [[Alliance Theatre]] from April 11 to May 13, 2012. A concept album was released the following year.\n*2013: ''[[Dolores Claiborne (opera)|Dolores Claiborne]]'' is an American [[opera]] composed by [[Tobias Picker]]. It premiered at the [[San Francisco Opera]] in Fall 2013.\n*2014: ''[[The Body (King novella)|The Body]]'' (also known as \"Stand By Me\") was produced by Chellaston Players in Derby, England. Though an amateur staging (produced with Stephen King's permission), it received rave reviews.\n\nThere have also been dramatizations of many of King's short stories, including \"[[Nona (short story)|Nona]]\", \"[[Quitters, Inc.]]\", \"[[In the Deathroom]]\", \"[[Strawberry Spring]]\", \"[[Harvey's Dream]]\", \"[[The Man Who Loved Flowers]]\", \"[[Mute (short story)|Mute]]\", \"[[The Ten O'Clock People]]\" and King's poem, \"[[Paranoid: A Chant]]\". There have also been alleged stage productions of ''Rage'' as well as several parody stage versions of ''[[The Shining (novel)|The Shining]]''.\n\n==Music==\n*1983: \"The Stand\", recorded by [[The Alarm]], and was released in the UK as a single. The song's lyrics were inspired by King's novel, ''[[The Stand]]''.\n*1985: \"Lone Justice\" by [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], is based on ''The Gunslinger''.\n*1984: \"Horror-Teria: (The Beginning)\" from the [[Twisted Sister]] album ''[[Stay Hungry (album)|Stay Hungry]]''. The album's liner notes thank King for inspiring the piece.\n*1987: \"Among the Living\", recorded by Anthrax, is based on ''The Stand''. \"The Walkin' Dude\" is Randall Flagg, the main villain in the book, and the beginning verse: \"Disease! Disease! Spreading the disease!\\With some help from Captain Trips\\He'll bring the world down to its knees\" refers to the virus that destroys most of the population in the novel.\n*1987: \"A Skeleton in the Closet\", recorded by Anthrax, is based on the King novella ''[[Apt Pupil]]'' from the collection ''[[Different Seasons]]''.\n*1987: \"Severed Survival\" recorded by [[Autopsy (band)|Autopsy]] is based on the King short story \"Survivor Type\".\n*1988: \"Misery Loves Company\" by [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], is based on ''Misery''\n*1989: \"[[Pet Sematary (song)|Pet Sematary]]\", recorded by The [[Ramones]], a single from their 1989 album ''[[Brain Drain (album)|Brain Drain]]''. The song is originally written for the King [[Pet Sematary (1989 film)|movie adaptation]] of the [[Pet Sematary|same name]]. The single became one of the Ramones' biggest radio hits, and a staple in their concerts during the 1990s.\n*1999: The music video for \"[[Spit It Out (Slipknot song)|Spit it Out]]\", recorded by [[nu metal]] band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], pays homage to Stanley Kubrick's adaptation of [[The Shining (film)|''The Shining'']]\n*2002: Formation of the Dutch band [[Delain]], who takes the name from Kingdom of Delain, from the novel ''[[The Eyes of the Dragon]]''\n*2006: The music video for [[The Kill]] by rock band [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]] is inspired by [[Stanley Kubrick|Stanley Kubrick's]] adaptation of [[The Shining (film)|The Shining]]\n*2006: The song \"Carry the Blessed Home\" on the [[Blind Guardian]] album ''[[A Twist in the Myth]]''. It is about [[Roland Deschain]] and [[Jake Chambers]] at the end of ''[[The Dark Tower (series)|The Dark Tower]]''.\n*2008: \"[[Dull Boy]]\", recorded by [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Mudvayne]], was a single for both ''[[The New Game]]'' and their compilation album, based on ''[[The Shining (novel)|The Shining]]'' novel and [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s [[The Shining (film)|1980 film]].\n*2015: Ice Nine Kills included the song \"Hell in the Hallways\" on their album ''Every Trick in the Book'', which was based on King's first novel ''Carrie''. A number of months later, the band via a poll created and released the single \"Enjoy Your Slay\", based upon ''The Shining''.\n*2016: The song \"Breathing Lightning\" by [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] is based on ''The Dark Tower'' series''.''\n*2016: Boston band Walter Sickert & the Army of Broken Toys included a song titled \"Dull Boy\" on their ''Come Black Magic'' album, with lyrics inspired by ''The Shining''. The song is otherwise unrelated to the Mudvayne track listed above.\n*2018: Ice Nine Kills release the album ''The Silver Scream'', featuring the song \"It is the End\", which is based upon the film and TV adaptations of King's highly successful horror novel ''[[It (novel)|It]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cite web|url=http://www.stephenking.com/promo/little_green_god_of_agony/|title=Little Green God of Agony \u2013 The Free Online eComic|year=2012|publisher=StephenKing.com|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Media based on Stephen King works}}\n{{Commons|Stephen King}}\n\n{{Media based on Stephen King works}}\n{{Stephen King}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Stephen}}\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by Stephen King| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of television series based on works]]\n[[Category:Lists of films based on works]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2015}}\nThis is a list of media based on work by [[Stephen King]] (including the [[Richard Bachman]] titles). Note that aside from ''[[Creepshow 2]]'', ''[[It Chapter Two]]'', and ''[[Doctor Sleep (2019 film)|Doctor Sleep]]'', the sequels are only tangentially related to Stephen King's work.\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Films\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Director\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Distributor\n! [[Rotten Tomatoes|RT]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|1970|1970s}}\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Carrie (1976 film)|Carrie]]''\n| [[Brian De Palma]]\n| [[Carrie (novel)|Based on the novel of the same name]]. \n| [[United Artists]]\n| 92%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1003625_carrie?|title=Carrie (1976)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|accessdate=November 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{sort|1980|1980s}}\n|-\