{"title_page": "Alexi Tuomarila", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|date=December 2017|reason=Translated from a bad Norwegian translation from German.}}\n[[File:Alexi Tuomarila.jpg|thumb|456x456px|Alexi Tuomarila, Finnish jazz pianist and composer.]]\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Alexi Tuomarila\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1974|02|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pori]], Finland\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| origin           = Finland\n| background       = temporary\n| instrument       = Piano\n| genre            = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Edition Records]], [[Svart Records]], [[Igloo Records]], [[Warner Music]], [[Jazzaway Records]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Alexi Tuomarila Trio]], [[Drifters (Swedish band)|Drifter]], [[Eero Koivistoinen Quartet]], [[Manuel Dunkel Quartet]], [[Lionel Beuvens MOTU]], [[AKT]]\n| website          = {{URL|www.alexituomarila.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexi Tuomarila''' (born 27 February 1974 in [[Pori]], Finland) is a Finnish jazz pianist and composer..\n\n== Biography ==\nAlexi Tuomarila started studying classical piano at the age of 6 at the [[Espoo]] Music Academy, Finland. As a teenager he was enthusiastic about rock and grunge music before digging deeper into jazz through his father's record collection. In 1993 Tuomarila was accepted to Oulunkyl\u00e4 pop/jazz Conservatory in [[Helsinki]], Finland, where he studied for a year. He continued his studies under [[Diederik Wissels]] and [[Nathalie Loriers]] at the [[Royal Conservatory of Brussels]] and earned his [[Master of Music]] degree in 1999.\n\nDuring his studies he formed his Quartet with [[Nicolas Kummert]], Christophe Devisscher, and Teun Verbruggen. In 1999 his quartet won the award for best band and Tuomarila won the prize for best soloist at the \"21st Hoeilaart International Jazz Competition\" Belgium. In 2001, he received the first prize at the \"3rd International Jazz Soloist Competition\" in [[Monaco]], and he won the \"10th International Tremplin Jazz Competition\" in [[Avignon]] with his quartet.\n\nThe Alexi Tuomarila Quartet also won the first prize at the \"5th International Granada Jazz Competition\" in Spain 2005.\n\nThe quartet recorded and released three albums \"Voices of Pohjola\" for [[Igloo Records]] (Benelux) 2001, the Emma Award (Finnish Grammy) nominee \"02\" for [[Finlandia Records]] - [[Warner Music Group]] 2003, and \"Runo X\" for Edita Cambeya (Spain) 2007.\n\nAlexi Tuomarila Quartet changed the name of the group into Drifter and welcomed Axel Gilain as a bass player/vocalist. Drifter recorded and released the critically acclaimed \"Flow\" album for [[Edition Records]], UK in 2015.\n\nIn 2005 Alexi Tuomarila formed his renowned trio, with Norwegian bassist [[Mats Eilertsen]] and Finnish drummer [[Olavi Louhivuori]]. The trio has released four critically acclaimed albums: \"Constellation\" for [[Jazzaway Records]] (Norway) 2006, and \"Seven Hills\" 2013, \"Kingdom\" 2017 and \"Sphere\" 2019 for distinguished British [[Edition Records]].\n\nThe latest album \"Sphere\" earned Tuomarila the prestigious [[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] (Finnish Grammy) for \"Jazz album of the year\".\n\nBritish [[BBC Music Magazine]] gave the album 5 stars and selected it as the \"Jazz album of the month\" (07/2019)\n\nAlexi Tuomarila played a decade, from 2007 until 2017, with the legendary Polish trumpet player [[Tomasz Sta\u0144ko]] in different kinds of band combinations. Their first concert together was at the 750th anniversary of the city of [[Krak\u00f3w]]. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wamNgEcXB6Y&list=PLkpvev7v9fArE6341iVOgkQyHxYkOMEbw]\n\nDuring 2009-2014 Tuomarila played with Tomasz Stanko Quintet ([[Jakob Bro]], Anders Christensen, [[Olavi Louhivuori]]) toured around the world and also recorded the Tomasz Stanko [[Dark Eyes (Tomasz Sta\u0144ko album)]] for [[ECM Records]], 2010,\n\nwhich reached number 5 in the Polish pop charts. [https://books.google.fi/books?id=OLyclzAaC-4C&pg=PT54&lpg=PT54&dq=tomasz+stanko+dark+eyes+polish+chart&source=bl&ots=qRunVI6Qr2&sig=ACfU3U3DQ-QmmUfVQu12JVyFx0K4MTPtKA&hl=fi&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil0of186joAhW0wsQBHXu9CtMQ6AEwEXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=tomasz%20stanko%20dark%20eyes%20polish%20chart&f=false]\n\nBetween 2015-2017 Tuomarila performed and toured with the Tomasz Stanko NY Quartet in Europe, China and Australia with [[Gerald Cleaver (musician)]] and [[Reuben Rogers]]\n\nTuomarila has also shared the stage with i.a. [[Eric Revis]], [[Thomas Morgan (bassist)]], [[Reggie Washington]], [[Joey Baron]], [[Kenny Wheeler]], [[Anders Jormin]], Kush Abadey, Nelson Veras, [[Perico Sambeat]], [[UMO Jazz Orchestra]], [[Eero Koivistoinen]], [[Peter Erskine]], [[Bill Evans (saxophonist)]] [[Anders Bergcrantz]], [[Rick Margitza]], [[Maciej Obara]].\n\n== Awards ==\n[[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] category Jazz Album of the year, Alexi Tuomarila Trio \"Sphere\" [[Edition Records]], UK, [http://jazzfinland.fi/news/jazz-emma-award-granted-for-alexi-tuomarila-trios-album-sphere]\n\n[[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] Nomination, Alexi Tuomarila Quartet \"02\" [[Finlandia Records]] - [[Warner Music Group]]\n\n1st Prize at \"3rd International Monaco Jazz soloist Competition\" [https://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/art-2000003974499.html]\n\n1st Prize at \"10th Tremplin International Jazz Competition\" Avignon, France, with Alexi Tuomarila Quartet [https://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/art-2000003987845.html]\n\n1st Prize at the \"5th International Granada Jazz Competition\", Spain, with Alexi Tuomarila Quartet [https://www.ts.fi/kulttuuri/1074074916/Alexi+Tuomarila+Quartet+voitti+Granadassa]\n\n1st Prize at the \"21st Hoeilaart International Jazz Competition\" Brussels, Belgium\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Solo Albums ===\n'''Alexi Tuomarila Trio''' ([[Mats Eilertsen]], [[Olavi Louhivuori]])\n\n2006: Constellation ([[Jazzaway Records]])\n\n2013: Seven Hills ([[Edition Records]])\n\n2017: Kingdom ([[Edition Records]])\n\n2019: Sphere ([[Edition Records]])\n\n'''Alexi Tuomarila Quartet''' ([[Nicolas Kummert]], Teun Verbruggen, Christophe Devisscher)\n\n2001: Voices of Pohjola ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n2003: 02 ([[Warner Jazz]] - [[Finlandia Records]])\n\n2007: Runo X (Edita Cambeya)\n\n'''Drifter''' (Axel Gilain, [[Nicolas Kummert]], Teun Verberuggen)\n\n2015: Flow ([[Edition Records]])\n\n'''Alvarado/Koivistoinen/Tuomarila''' ([[Eero Koivistoinen]], Martin Alvarado)\n\n2019: Alma ([[Svart Records]])\n\n=== Collaborations ===\n'''[[Tomasz Sta\u0144ko|Tomasz Sta\u0144ko Quintet]] ([[Anders Christensen]], [[Jakob Bro]], Olavi Louhivuori)'''\n\n\u2022 2010: [[Dark Eyes (Tomasz Sta\u0144ko album)]] ([[ECM Records]] - ECM 2115)\n\n'''Lithium''' ([[Andr\u00e9 Fernandes]], Joonas Tuuri, Jonne Taavitsainen)\n\n\u2022 2018: Red ([[Challenge Records (1994)]]\n\n'''[[Eero Koivistoinen]]''' '''Quartet''' (Jussi Lehtonen, Jori Huhtala)\n\n\u2022 2014: Hati Hati ([[Svart Records]])\n\n\u2022 2016: Illusions ([[Svart Records]])\n\n'''Manuel Dunkel Quartet''' (Teppo M\u00e4kynen, Ville Huolman, Jaska Lukkarinen, Eero Sepp\u00e4)\n\n\u2022 2010: A Step Forward (Texicalli Records)\n\n\u2022 2019: Discoveries (Eclipse Music)\n\n'''Lionel Beuvens MOTU''' (Kalevi Louhivuori, Brice Soniano, Natashia Kelly, Guilhem Verger)\n\n\u2022 2013: Trinite ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n\u2022 2017: Earthsong ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n'''[[Andr\u00e9 Fernandes]] Dream Keeper''' ([[Perico Sambeat]], Demian Cabaud, Iago Fernandes)\n\n\u2022 2016: Dream Keeper ([[Edition Records]])\n\n'''[[Mats Eilertsen]] SkyDive Quintet''' ([[Tore Brunborg]], [[Thomas T. Dahl]], [[Olavi Louhivuori]])\n\n\u2022 2014: SkyDive (Hubro Music)\n\n'''[[Nicolas Kummert]] Voices''' (Herve Samb, Jens Maurits Bouttery, [[Nicolas Thys]])\n\n\u2022 2014: Liberte (Prova Records)\n\n'''Andre Sumelius Quartet''' (Ernesto Aurignac, Marko Lohikari)\n\n\u2022 2010: Victory Songs (Abovoice)\n\n'''[[Tolonen]]''' (Timo K\u00e4m\u00e4r\u00e4inen, Teemu Viinikainen, Risto Toppola, Joonatan Rautio, Manuel Dunkel, Juho Kivivuori, Sampo Tiittanen, Ville Pynssi)\n\n\u2022 2013: Tolonen ([[Gateway Films/Vision Video]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Philippe Carles, Andr\u00e9 Clergeat, Jean-Louis Comolli: ''Le nouveau fors\u00f8k du jazz''. R. Laffont: Paris, 2011.\n\n== External links ==\nOfficial website: http://www.alexituomarila.com\n\nRecord Label: http://www.editionrecords.com/alexituomarila\n\nJazz Finland: http://jazzfinland.fi/artist/alexi-tuomarila\u00a0 \u00a0 {{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuomarila, Alexi}}\n[[Category:Finnish jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:Finnish jazz composers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup|date=December 2017|reason=Translated from a bad Norwegian translation from German.}}\n[[File:Alexi Tuomarila.jpg|thumb|456x456px|Alexi Tuomarila, Finnish jazz pianist and composer.]]\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Alexi Tuomarila\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1974|02|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Pori]], Finland\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| origin           = Finland\n| background       = temporary\n| instrument       = Piano\n| genre            = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Edition Records]], [[Svart Records]], [[Igloo Records]], [[Warner Music]], [[Jazzaway Records]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Alexi Tuomarila Trio]], [[Drifters (Swedish band)|Drifter]], [[Eero Koivistoinen Quartet]], [[Manuel Dunkel Quartet]], [[Lionel Beuvens MOTU]], [[AKT]]\n| website          = {{URL|www.alexituomarila.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexi Tuomarila''' (born 27 February 1974 in [[Pori]], Finland) is a Finnish jazz pianist and composer..\n\n== Biography ==\nAlexi Tuomarila started studying classical piano at the age of 6 at the [[Espoo]] Music Academy, Finland. As a teenager he was enthusiastic about rock and grunge music before digging deeper into jazz through his father's record collection. In 1993 Tuomarila was accepted to Oulunkyl\u00e4 pop/jazz Conservatory in [[Helsinki]], Finland, where he studied for a year. He continued his studies under [[Diederik Wissels]] and [[Nathalie Loriers]] at the [[Royal Conservatory of Brussels]] and earned his [[Master of Music]] degree in 1999. \n\nDuring his studies he formed his Quartet with [[Nicolas Kummert]], Christophe Devisscher, and Teun Verbruggen. In 1999 his quartet won the award for best band and Tuomarila won the prize for best soloist at the \"21st Hoeilaart International Jazz Competition\" Belgium. In 2001, he received the first prize at the \"3rd International Jazz Soloist Competition\" in [[Monaco]], and he won the \"10th International Tremplin Jazz Competition\" in [[Avignon]] with his quartet. \n\nThe Alexi Tuomarila Quartet also won the first prize at the \"5th International Granada Jazz Competition\" in Spain 2005. \n\nThe quartet recorded and released three albums \"Voices of Pohjola\" for [[Igloo Records]] (Benelux) 2001, the Emma Award (Finnish Grammy) nominee \"02\" for [[Finlandia Records]] - [[Warner Music Group]] 2003, and \"Runo X\" for Edita Cambeya (Spain) 2007. \n\nAlexi Tuomarila Quartet changed the name of the group into Drifter and welcomed Axel Gilain as a bass player/vocalist. Drifter recorded and released the critically acclaimed \"Flow\" album for [[Edition Records]], UK in 2015.\n\nIn 2005 Alexi Tuomarila formed his renowned trio, with Norwegian bassist [[Mats Eilertsen]] and Finnish drummer [[Olavi Louhivuori]]. The trio has released four critically acclaimed albums: \"Constellation\" for [[Jazzaway Records]] (Norway) 2006, and \"Seven Hills\" 2013, \"Kingdom\" 2017 and \"Sphere\" 2019 for distinguished British [[Edition Records]]. \n\nThe latest album \"Sphere\" earned Tuomarila the prestigious [[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] (Finnish Grammy) for \"Jazz album of the year\". \n\nBritish [[BBC Music Magazine]] gave the album 5 stars and selected it as the \"Jazz album of the month\" (07/2019)\n\nAlexi Tuomarila played a decade, from 2007 until 2017, with the legendary Polish trumpet player [[Tomasz Sta\u0144ko]] in different kinds of band combinations. Their first concert together was at the 750th anniversary of the city of [[Krak\u00f3w]]. [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wamNgEcXB6Y&list=PLkpvev7v9fArE6341iVOgkQyHxYkOMEbw] \n\nDuring 2009-2014 Tuomarila played with Tomasz Stanko Quintet ([[Jakob Bro]], Anders Christensen, [[Olavi Louhivuori]]) toured around the world and also recorded the Tomasz Stanko [[Dark Eyes (Tomasz Sta\u0144ko album)]] for [[ECM Records]], 2010, \n\nwhich reached number 5 in the Polish pop charts. [https://books.google.fi/books?id=OLyclzAaC-4C&pg=PT54&lpg=PT54&dq=tomasz+stanko+dark+eyes+polish+chart&source=bl&ots=qRunVI6Qr2&sig=ACfU3U3DQ-QmmUfVQu12JVyFx0K4MTPtKA&hl=fi&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwil0of186joAhW0wsQBHXu9CtMQ6AEwEXoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=tomasz%20stanko%20dark%20eyes%20polish%20chart&f=false]\n\nBetween 2015-2017 Tuomarila performed and toured with the Tomasz Stanko NY Quartet in Europe, China and Australia with [[Gerald Cleaver (musician)]] and [[Reuben Rogers]] \n\nTuomarila has also shared the stage with i.a. [[Eric Revis]], [[Thomas Morgan (bassist)]], [[Reggie Washington]], [[Joey Baron]], [[Kenny Wheeler]], [[Anders Jormin]], Kush Abadey, Nelson Veras, [[Perico Sambeat]], [[UMO Jazz Orchestra]], [[Eero Koivistoinen]], [[Peter Erskine]], [[Bill Evans (saxophonist)]] [[Anders Bergcrantz]], [[Rick Margitza]], [[Maciej Obara]]. \n== Awards ==\n[[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] category Jazz Album of the year, Alexi Tuomarila Trio \"Sphere\" [[Edition Records]], UK, [http://jazzfinland.fi/news/jazz-emma-award-granted-for-alexi-tuomarila-trios-album-sphere]\n\n[[Emma-gaala|Emma award]] Nomination, Alexi Tuomarila Quartet \"02\" [[Finlandia Records]] - [[Warner Music Group]] \n\n1st Prize at \"3rd International Monaco Jazz soloist Competition\" [https://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/art-2000003974499.html]  \n\n1st Prize at \"10th Tremplin International Jazz Competition\" Avignon, France, with Alexi Tuomarila Quartet [https://www.hs.fi/kulttuuri/art-2000003987845.html] \n\n1st Prize at the \"5th International Granada Jazz Competition\", Spain, with Alexi Tuomarila Quartet [https://www.ts.fi/kulttuuri/1074074916/Alexi+Tuomarila+Quartet+voitti+Granadassa]\n\n1st Prize at the \"21st Hoeilaart International Jazz Competition\" Brussels, Belgium  \n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== '''Solo Albums''' ===\n'''Alexi Tuomarila Trio''' ([[Mats Eilertsen]], [[Olavi Louhivuori]])\n\n2006: Constellation ([[Jazzaway Records]])\n\n2013: Seven Hills ([[Edition Records]])\n\n2017: Kingdom ([[Edition Records]])\n\n2019: Sphere ([[Edition Records]])\n\n\n\n'''Alexi Tuomarila Quartet''' ([[Nicolas Kummert]], Teun Verbruggen, Christophe Devisscher)\n\n2001: Voices of Pohjola ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n2003: 02 ([[Warner Jazz]] - [[Finlandia Records]])\n\n2007: Runo X (Edita Cambeya)\n\n\n\n'''Drifter''' (Axel Gilain, [[Nicolas Kummert]], Teun Verberuggen)\n\n2015: Flow ([[Edition Records]])\n\n\n\n'''Alvarado/Koivistoinen/Tuomarila''' ([[Eero Koivistoinen]], Martin Alvarado)\n\n2019: Alma ([[Svart Records]])<br />\n\n=== Collaborations ===\n'''[[Tomasz Sta\u0144ko|Tomasz Sta\u0144ko Quintet]] ([[Anders Christensen]], [[Jakob Bro]], Olavi Louhivuori)'''\n\n\u2022 2010: [[Dark Eyes (Tomasz Sta\u0144ko album)]] ([[ECM Records]] - ECM 2115)\n\n\n'''Lithium''' ([[Andr\u00e9 Fernandes]], Joonas Tuuri, Jonne Taavitsainen)\n\n\u2022 2018: Red ([[Challenge Records (1994)]]\n\n\n'''[[Eero Koivistoinen]]''' '''Quartet''' (Jussi Lehtonen, Jori Huhtala)\n\n\u2022 2014: Hati Hati ([[Svart Records]])\n\n\u2022 2016: Illusions ([[Svart Records]])\n\n\n\n'''Manuel Dunkel Quartet''' (Teppo M\u00e4kynen, Ville Huolman, Jaska Lukkarinen, Eero Sepp\u00e4)\n\n\u2022 2010: A Step Forward (Texicalli Records)\n\n\u2022 2019: Discoveries (Eclipse Music)\n\n'''Lionel Beuvens MOTU''' (Kalevi Louhivuori, Brice Soniano, Natashia Kelly, Guilhem Verger)\n\n\u2022 2013: Trinite ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n\u2022 2017: Earthsong ([[Igloo Records]])\n\n\n\n'''[[Andr\u00e9 Fernandes]] Dream Keeper''' ([[Perico Sambeat]], Demian Cabaud, Iago Fernandes)\n\n\u2022 2016: Dream Keeper ([[Edition Records]])\n\n\n\n'''[[Mats Eilertsen]] SkyDive Quintet''' ([[Tore Brunborg]], [[Thomas T. Dahl]], [[Olavi Louhivuori]])\n\n\u2022 2014: SkyDive (Hubro Music)\n\n\n\n'''[[Nicolas Kummert]] Voices''' (Herve Samb, Jens Maurits Bouttery, [[Nicolas Thys]])\n\n\u2022 2014: Liberte (Prova Records)\n\n\n\n'''Andre Sumelius Quartet''' (Ernesto Aurignac, Marko Lohikari)\n\n\u2022 2010: Victory Songs (Abovoice)\n\n\n\n'''[[Tolonen]]''' (Timo K\u00e4m\u00e4r\u00e4inen, Teemu Viinikainen, Risto Toppola, Joonatan Rautio, Manuel Dunkel, Juho Kivivuori, Sampo Tiittanen, Ville Pynssi)\n\n\u2022 2013: Tolonen ([[Gateway Films/Vision Video]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Philippe Carles, Andr\u00e9 Clergeat, Jean-Louis Comolli: ''Le nouveau fors\u00f8k du jazz''. R. Laffont: Paris, 2011.\n\n== External link ==\nOfficial website: http://www.alexituomarila.com\n\nRecord Label: http://www.editionrecords.com/alexituomarila\n\nJazz Finland: http://jazzfinland.fi/artist/alexi-tuomarila\u00a0 \u00a0 {{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuomarila, Alexi}}\n[[Category:Finnish jazz pianists]]\n[[Category:Finnish jazz composers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Heading with bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexi_Tuomarila"}
{"title_page": "Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9", "text_new": "'''Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9''' n\u00e9e de Romanet (1733\u20131753), was a French courtier, [[Ma\u00eetresse-en-titre|mistress]] to [[Louis XV of France]] in 1752. \n\nShe was the daughter of Pierre-Jean de Romanet (1685\u20131751) and Marie-Charlotte d'Estrades (1696-?). She married count Fran\u00e7ois-Martial de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9 (1717\u20131791) in 1751. She was the niece of [[Elisabeth d'Estrades]], a confidant of [[Madame de Pompadour]] and lover of minister [[Marc-Pierre de Voyer de Paulmy d'Argenson]]. She was appointed lady-in-waiting to the king's daughters, the ''[[Mesdames]]''. \n\nShe was launched by d'Estrades and d'Argenson as a candidate to replace Madame de Pompadour as the official mistress of the King, at a point when the sexual relationship between Pompadour and king the was discontinued and the king had started to acquire unofficial lovers to [[Parc-aux-Cerfs]]. She did have sex with the king in the summer of 1752 on [[Palace of Fontainebleau]]. Her husband's relative, [[\u00c9tienne Fran\u00e7ois, duc de Choiseul]], exposed the plot to Pompadour, who in turn had the king banish Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9 from court; she died in childbirth the following year. The incident attracted much attention at the time and was the first woman treated seriously as a rival by Madame de Pompadour; the next and last would be [[Marie Anne de Coislin]]. \n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* Lever, Evelyne, Madame de Pompadour, Perrin, Paris, 2000\n\n{{Expand Swedish|Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9, Charlotte Rosalie de }}\n\n[[Category:1733 births]]\n[[Category:1753 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of Louis XV of France]]\n[[Category:French ladies-in-waiting]]\n", "text_old": "'''Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9''' n\u00e9e de Romanet (1733\u20131753), was a French courtier, [[Ma\u00eetresse-en-titre|mistress]] to [[Louis XV of France]] in 1752. \n\nShe was the daughter of Pierre-Jean de Romanet (1685\u20131751) and Marie-Charlotte d'Estrades (1696-?). She married count Fran\u00e7ois-Martial de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9 (1717\u20131791) in 1751. She was the niece of [[Elisabeth d'Estrades]], a confidant of [[Madame de Pompadour]] and lover of minister [[Marc-Pierre de Voyer de Paulmy d'Argenson]]. She was appointed lady-in-waiting to the king's daughters, the ''[[Mesdames]]''. \n\nShe was launched by d'Estrades and d'Argenson as a candidate to replace Madame de Pompadour as the official mistress of the King, at a point when the sexual relationship between Pompadour and king the was discontinued and the king had started to acquire inofficial lovers to [[Parc-aux-Cerfs]]. She did have sex with the king in the summer of 1752 on [[Palace of Fontainebleau]]. Her husband's relative, [[\u00c9tienne Fran\u00e7ois, duc de Choiseul]], exposed the plot to Pompadour, who in turn had the king banish Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9 from court; she died in childbirth the following year. The incident attracted much attention at the time and was the first woman treated seriously as a rival by Madame de Pompadour; the next and last would be [[Marie Anne de Coislin]]. \n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* Lever, Evelyne, Madame de Pompadour, Perrin, Paris, 2000\n\n{{Expand Swedish|Charlotte Rosalie de Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choiseul-Beaupr\u00e9, Charlotte Rosalie de }}\n\n[[Category:1733 births]]\n[[Category:1753 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of Louis XV of France]]\n[[Category:French ladies-in-waiting]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: inofficial->unofficial", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlotte_Rosalie_de_Choiseul-Beaupr%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Miradero, Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico", "text_new": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Miradero\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = Joyuda, Miradero, Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico.jpg\n| image_caption            = [[Joyuda, Puerto Rico|Joyuda]] in Miradero\n| image_flag               = Bandera del Barrio Miradero, Cabo Rojo.jpg\n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = Escudo de Miradero, Cabo Rojo.jpg\n| seal_size                = 70\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = \n| mapsize                  = \n| map_caption              = \n| image_map1               = \n| mapsize1                 = \n| map_caption1             =\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.090725800000001|-67.178244699999993|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415681|Miradero}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area)|Commonwealth]]\n| subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n| subdivision_type2        = [[List of municipalities in Puerto Rico|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name2        = {{flagicon image|Flag of Cabo Rojo.svg}} [[Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico|Cabo Rojo]]\n<!-- Politics --------------- -->\n| government_footnotes     =\n| government_type          =\n| leader_title             = \n| leader_name              = \n| established_title        = \n| established_date         = \n<!-- Area    ------------------- -->\n| area_magnitude           = 1 E7\n| unit_pref                = Imperial\n| area_footnotes           =\n| area_total_km2           = \n| area_land_km2            = \n| area_water_km2           = \n| area_total_sq_mi         =  \n| area_land_sq_mi          =  \n| area_water_sq_mi         =  \n| area_water_percent       = \n| area_urban_km2           =\n| area_urban_sq_mi         =\n| area_metro_km2           =\n| area_metro_sq_mi         =\n| area_blank1_title        =\n| area_blank1_km2          =\n| area_blank1_sq_mi        =\n<!-- Population   --------------------- -->\n| population_as_of         = 2010\n| population_footnotes     = \n| population_note          = Source: 2010 Census\n<!-- USE OF COMMA FOR THE FIELD BELOW IS OPTIONAL -------- -->\n| population_total         = 15521\n| population_density_km2   = \n<!-- DO NOT USE COMMAS FOR THE POPULATION DENSITY BELOW -- -->\n| population_density_sq_mi =  \n| population_metro         = \n| population_density_metro_km2     =\n| population_density_metro_sq_mi   =\n| population_urban                 =\n| population_density_urban_km2     =\n| population_density_urban_sq_mi   =\n| population_blank1_title          =\n| population_blank1                =\n| population_density_blank1_km2    =\n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi  =\n<!-- General information  ------------- -->\n| timezone                 = [[Atlantic Time Zone|AST]]\n| utc_offset               = &minus;4\n| timezone_DST             = \n| utc_offset_DST           = \n| latd =\n| longd =\n| elevation_footnotes      = \n| elevation_m              = \n| elevation_ft             = 49\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others ------ -->\n| postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code              = 00623\n| area_code                = \n| website                  = \n| footnotes                =\n}}\n'''Miradero''' is a [[Barrios of Puerto Rico|barrio]] in the municipality of [[Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico]]. Its population in 2010 was 15,521.<ref name=\"Pico_1969\">{{cite book |last1=Pic\u00f3 |first1=Rafael |last2=Buitrago de Santiago |first2=Zayda |last3=Berrios |first3=Hector H. |title=Nueva geograf\u00eda de Puerto Rico: f\u00edsica, econ\u00f3mica, y social, por Rafael Pic\u00f3. Con la colaboraci\u00f3n de Zayda Buitrago de Santiago y H\u00e9ctor H. Berrios. |url=https://archive.org/details/nuevageografad00pic/page/247|publisher=San Juan Editorial Universitaria, Universidad de Puerto Rico,1969}}</ref><ref name=\"Law2015\">{{cite book|author=Gwillim Law|title=Administrative Subdivisions of Countries: A Comprehensive World Reference, 1900 through 1998| url =https://books.google.com/books?id=nXCeCQAAQBAJ|accessdate=25 December 2018|date=20 May 2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-0447-3|page=300}}</ref><ref name= \"2010 Census\">{{cite book|title=Puerto Rico:2010:population and housing unit counts.pdf | url = https://permanent.access.gpo.gov/gpo35934/cph-2-53.pdf|year=2010|publisher=U.S. Dept. of Commerce, Economics and Statistics Administration, U.S. Census Bureau}}</ref>\n\n==Plaza and gastronomic route==\nThere is a square called {{lang|es|Plaza del Pescador}} in Miradero which happens to be the venue for the annual {{lang|es|Festival del pescao}} (the festival of the fish).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vocesdelsurpr.com/2019/07/cabo-rojo-celebrara-la-edicion-49-de-la-fiesta-del-pescao/|title=Cabo Rojo celebrar\u00e1 la edici\u00f3n 49 de la Fiesta del Pescao|first=Sara Marrero|last=Caban|date=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nJoyuda, a fishing village in Miradero is known for its many seafood restaurants along [[Puerto Rico Highway 102]], a coastal road.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discoveringpuertorico.com/joyuda-a-must-for-seafood-lovers/|title=Joyuda Seafood Restaurants &#124; Discovering Puerto Rico}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[United States]] acquired Puerto Rico from [[Spain]] in the aftermath of the [[Spanish-American War]] under the terms of the [[Treaty of Paris (1898)|Treaty of Paris of 1898]] and conducted its first [[census]] of Puerto Rico, finding that the population of Miradero barrio was 2,011.<ref name=\"OfficeSanger1900\">{{cite book|author1=Joseph Prentiss Sanger|author2=Henry Gannett|author3=Walter Francis Willcox|title=Informe sobre el censo de Puerto Rico, 1899, United States. War Dept. Porto Rico Census Office|url=https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog|year=1900|publisher=Imprenta del gobierno|page=[https://archive.org/details/informesobreelc00joangoog/page/n255 164]| language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nPlaza del Pescador - Puerto Real, Cabo Rojo.jpg|Plaza del Pescador in Miradero\nTorre Puesta del Sol - Poblado Joyuda, Cabo Rojo.jpg|Joyuda, Miradero\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of communities in Puerto Rico]]\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Puerto Rico}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Barrios of Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Barrio of Puerto Rico}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n<!-- Basic info  -------------- -->\n| official_name            = Miradero\n| settlement_type          = Barrio\n<!-- images and maps  --------- -->\n| image_skyline            = Joyuda, Miradero, Cabo Rojo, Puerto Rico.jpg\n| image_caption            = [[Joyuda, Puerto Rico|Joyuda]] in Miradero\n| image_flag               = Bandera del Barrio Miradero, Cabo Rojo.jpg\n| flag_size                =\n| image_seal               = Escudo de Miradero, Cabo Rojo.jpg\n| seal_size                = 70\n| image_blank_emblem       =\n| blank_emblem_type        =\n| blank_emblem_size        =\n| image_map                = \n| mapsize                  = \n| map_caption              = \n| image_map1               = \n| mapsize1                 = \n| map_caption1             =\n| pushpin_map              = Puerto Rico\n| coordinates              = {{coord|18.090725800000001|-67.178244699999993|region:US-PR|format=dms|display=inline, title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes    = <ref>{{Gnis|2415681|Miradero}}</ref>\n<!-- Location ---------------- -->\n| subdivision_type1        = [[Commonwealth (U.S. insular area